A tree-sitter grammar is executable tooling metadata. A minimal grammar sketch looks like:

```javascript
module.exports = grammar({
  name: "example",
  rules: {
    source_file: $ => repeat($.item),
    item: $ => choice($.function_item, $.struct_item),
    function_item: $ => seq("fn", $.identifier, $.parameter_list, $.block),
    parameter_list: $ => seq("(", optional(sepBy(",", $.parameter)), ")"),
    expression: $ => choice($.identifier, $.number, $.binary_expression),
    binary_expression: $ => prec.left(seq($.expression, $.operator, $.expression))
  }
});
```

The generic lesson is that an editor grammar is not just a recognizer. It is a contract for highlighting, structural selection, navigation, injections, folds, and query-based tooling. Naming nodes and fields carefully matters because queries will depend on those names for years.
